{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17646965","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17646965"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:39:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:39:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18222"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18222","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18222"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.22,0.06,0.56,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10936"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114268"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10936"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18222"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96268"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4929"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5113"},{"type":"tags","id":"10214"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25418"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25421"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114268"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following substances increases calcium uptake into bone and regulates normal bone turnover?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["25-hydroxyvitamin D3","Vitamin D3","7-dehydrocholesterol","1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3","Vitamin D2"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3\u003C/strong\u003E, also known as calcitriol, is the active form of vitamin D. It plays a crucial role in calcium homeostasis by increasing calcium absorption in the intestines and promoting calcium uptake into bone, thereby regulating normal bone turnover.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D3\u003C/strong\u003E (cholecalciferol) is the form of vitamin D synthesised in the skin upon exposure to sunlight. It is converted in the liver to 25-hydroxyvitamin D3, which is then further converted in the kidneys to the active form, 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E25-hydroxyvitamin D3\u003C/strong\u003E is the main circulating form of vitamin D and is used to assess vitamin D status. However, it is not the active form that directly increases calcium uptake into bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E7-dehydrocholesterol\u003C/strong\u003E is a precursor of vitamin D3, which is synthesised in the skin upon exposure to ultraviolet B radiation from sunlight. It does not directly influence calcium uptake into bone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin D2\u003C/strong\u003E (ergocalciferol) is another form of vitamin D found in some plants and fungi. Like vitamin D3, it must be converted to its active form to exert its effects on calcium metabolism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3 (calcitriol) is the active form of vitamin D that increases calcium absorption in the intestines and promotes calcium uptake into bone.","Vitamin D3 (cholecalciferol) is converted in the liver to 25-hydroxyvitamin D3, which is then converted in the kidneys to the active form, 1,25-dihydroxyvitamin D3.","7-dehydrocholesterol is a precursor of vitamin D3, which is synthesised in the skin upon exposure to sunlight."],"references":["Khurana I, Khurana A, Kowlgi NG. Textbook of Medical Physiology_-E-book. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2019.","Clarke B. Normal bone anatomy and physiology. Clin J Am Soc Nephrol. 2008 Nov;3 Suppl 3(Suppl 3):S131-9.","Florencio-Silva R, Sasso GR, Sasso-Cerri E, Sim\u00f5es MJ, Cerri PS. Biology of Bone Tissue: Structure, Function, and Factors That Influence Bone Cells. Biomed Res Int. 2015;2015:421746.","Cowan PT, Launico MV, Kahai P. Anatomy, Bones. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. [Updated 2024 Apr 21]."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96268"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18222"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96268","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96268"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-15T14:31:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-15T14:32:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10936"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114268"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","